            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Isabella Rossi is a San Franciscan in her bones, the product of two of the city's vibrant, hardworking cultures. Her father, the son of Italian immigrants, ran a beloved bakery in North Beach, while her mother, who arrived from the Philippines in the 1970s, worked as a compassionate and respected nurse at SF General. Growing up in the Outer Richmond, Isabella\u2019s childhood was a blend of boisterous family dinners, the scent of focaccia, and a deep-seated respect for both science and community.\n\nInspired by her mother\u2019s work but drawn more to molecules than to patients, she pursued a biochemistry degree at UC Davis. Her career began at the lab bench of a small South San Francisco biotech startup. While she excelled at research, she discovered her true talent was in seeing the bigger picture. A key turning point came when she volunteered to manage a struggling project, untangling logistical knots with an efficiency that surprised her superiors. This success steered her away from the microscope and toward management.\n\nNow 42, Isabella is the Associate Director of Clinical Operations at a major pharmaceutical firm in Mission Bay. She shepherds life-saving drugs through the labyrinthine trial process, a high-pressure role she finds deeply rewarding. Her life is one of structured discipline. Weekdays begin with the rumble of a MUNI bus from her chic Hayes Valley apartment, a commute she uses for reading or mentally outlining her day. Evenings are for unwinding with yoga, attempting her father\u2019s recipes, or meeting her tight-knit group of friends for dinner.\n\nThough she had a significant relationship that ended amicably in her thirties, Isabella is currently single and content, focusing on her career and nurturing her friendships. She is deeply connected to a San Francisco that is both old and new\u2014she\u2019ll grab artisanal coffee in the morning but spend her Sunday visiting her retired parents in the same house where she grew up. Her dream is to one day lead a team that brings an Alzheimer's drug to market, a goal inspired by the grandmother she lost. She aspires not just to climb the corporate ladder, but to feel she has left a tangible, positive mark on the world."
